Field Automation: Manual Override
To distinguish between system-generated data and user-defined adjustments, a Manual Override checkbox will be implemented on the Account Landscape object.

Manual Detection: This indicator will be automatically toggled to TRUE if a user manually modifies the Competitor Revenues field.
Audit Purpose: This flag informs the system and other stakeholders that the displayed revenue figures may deviate from the automated average calculation derived from the related Competitor Assets
Field Automation: Pending Mapping
The Pending Mapping (Boolean) field on the Account Landscape object serves as an indicator of whether a competitor's footprint has been identified for a specific Account and Business Unit (BU).

Initialization Logic: By default, this field is set to TRUE upon record creation.
Before-Insert Trigger: Prior to commitment, the system will verify the existence of any Asset record where:
RecordType = "Competitor"
AccountId = [Account Landscape Account]
Business Unit = [Account Landscape Business Unit]
Outcome: If at least one matching Asset is found, the Pending Mapping field shall be set to FALSE.
To ensure financial accuracy, the system will dynamically calculate and update the Competitor Revenues field on the Account Landscape record whenever a Competitor Asset is managed.

Triggering Event: Insertion of an Asset (RecordType = "Competitor").

Automation Logic:

Aggregation: The system will query all Asset records with the "Competitor" RecordType associated with the same Account and Business Unit.
Calculation: It will calculate the average revenue/value from these assets.
Update:
The resulting average is mapped to the Competitor Revenues field in the corresponding Account Landscape record.
Simultaneously, the Pending Mapping flag is toggled to FALSE, as the presence of competitor instruments is now confirmed and quantified.
Account Segmentation: Customer’s Segmentation
To define the different segmentation types and their associated values, a new custom object Account Segmentation Reference will be used. Access to create categories within the segmentation administration will be granted only to specific users.

Key fields include:

Type - Picklist: Global, Local - Required field
Business Unit - Global Picklist - Required field
Segmentation - Text (f.e) "Cardiovascular Surgery" - Required field
Business Segmentation Comments - Text Area
Logic will be implemented to ensure that each segmentation remains unique in its type, and associated business unit.

To register a customer’s segmentation, a new custom object Account Segmentation with the Record Type Customer’s Segmentation will be required. This object will allow a customer to be linked to a specific Segmentation.

Key fields include:

Account Segmentation Reference - Account Segmentation Reference Lookup - Required field
Account - master‑detail relationship to Account
Type - Picklist: Autopopulate Reference Type
Business Unit - Picklist: Autopopulate Reference Business Unit
Segment - Formula: Reference Segmentation + (Reference Type) (f.e) "Cardiovascular Surgery (Global)"
Value - Checkbox: false default
Business Segmentation Comments - Text Area
External Id - Text. Unique. ExternalId Account Segmentation Reference + Id - to prevent duplicates.
The business line field has been removed when the values ​​of the business unit "Other" were modified as new business units, so it no longer makes sense to report this field.

Duplicate controls will be established to prohibit the creation of identical ReferenceIds under a single Account record.

